# Issue a credential

Complete these steps in order. Some steps cannot be tested until earlier steps are live and accessible.

If you have not already read [before you issue a credential](/before-integrating), start there. It explains what you need to build, what to arrange with the GOV.UK Wallet team, and what must be in place before end-to-end testing.

## Implementation sequence

### 1. Authenticate users with GOV.UK One Login

[Authenticate users with GOV.UK One Login](authenticate-users/)

You must authenticate users with GOV.UK One Login before you can issue a credential. This step retrieves the user's `walletSubjectId`, which your service uses later to confirm it is issuing the credential to the correct wallet.

### 2. Generate a credential offer

[Generate a credential offer](credential-offer/)

Your service generates a signed credential offer containing a pre-authorised code and displays it to the user as a QR code or deep link. This is the entry point that triggers GOV.UK Wallet to start the credential request flow.

### 3. Publish your metadata

[Publish your metadata](metadata/)

You must publish a metadata endpoint at `GET /.well-known/openid-credential-issuer`. GOV.UK Wallet fetches this endpoint before it requests a credential, to find your credential endpoint and understand what credential types your service supports.

### 4. Publish your JSON Web Key Set (JWKS)

[Publish your JSON Web Key Set (JWKS)](jwks/)

You must publish your public keys at `GET /.well-known/jwks.json`. GOV.UK One Login fetches this endpoint to verify the signature on the pre-authorised code your service generates. This endpoint must be live before GOV.UK One Login can exchange a pre-authorised code for an access token.

### 5. Issue a credential

[Issue a credential](credential/)

You must build a `POST /credential` endpoint that receives credential requests from GOV.UK Wallet and returns a signed, device-bound credential. This is the most complex step — allow your team time to read the guidance before starting.

<%= warning_text('Your metadata (step 3) and JWKS (step 4) endpoints must be live and publicly accessible before GOV.UK Wallet can successfully call your credential endpoint.') %>

If you are issuing an mdoc-based credential — such as the mobile driving licence — you also need to follow the mdoc-specific credential construction guidance:

- [Create an mdoc credential](mdoc/) — how to encode data elements, build the Mobile Security Object (MSO), and sign with COSE_Sign1
- [Issue a credential with a custom namespace](mdoc/custom-namespace/) — if your credential type does not use ISO 18013-5.1 standard driving licence attributes

### 6. Publish your DID document

[Publish your decentralised identifier (DID) document](did/)

You must publish your public key as a DID document at `GET /.well-known/did.json`. GOV.UK Wallet fetches this endpoint after receiving your credential, to verify the signature on it. You can use the same key pair as your JWKS, or a separate one.

### 7. Handle notifications (optional)

[Handle notifications from GOV.UK Wallet](notification/)

If you implement a `POST /notification` endpoint, GOV.UK Wallet will send your service a callback to confirm whether it successfully stored the credential. This step is optional. Implement it last, once the core issuance flow is working end-to-end.
